Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Mobuolafoluwa Onayade¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data set has information on

  • Duration of the bike rides in seconds
  • Start_time of the ride
  • End_time of the ride
  • Start station id

  • Start station name

  • Start station's latitude

  • Start station's longitude

  • End station id

  • End station name

  • End station's latitude

  • End station's longitude

  • Bike id

  • User type: subscriber or customer

  • Member birth year

  • Member gender

  • Bike share for all trip

    # Helper function to inspect and assess the data characteristics
def get_data_summary(data):
    summary = pd.concat([data.dtypes, data.nunique(),
                         data.count(), data.isnull().sum()],
                        keys=["dtypes", "nunique", "count", "missing"],
                        axis=1)
    return summary

    What is the structure of your dataset?¶

    The dataset contains 183,412 bike rides records with 16 characteristics (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip). The dataset has both numeric and categorical variables

    What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • Average duration of bike rides

  • Age and gender distribution of riders

  • Time of the day majority of the rides were taken

  • Association between user type and the duration of rides

    What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Duration_sec

  • Member_birth_year

  • Member_gender

  • Start_time

  • user_type

    In [10]:
    # Categorize the hour into time of the day 
b = [0,6,12,18,24]
l = ['Late Night','Morning','Afternoon','Night']
data['time_of_day'] = pd.cut(data['time'], bins=b, labels=l, include_lowest=True)

# Define the variable inputs
def f(x):
    if (x > 6) and (x <= 12 ):
        return 'Morning'
    elif (x > 12) and (x <= 18):
        return'Afternoon'
    elif (x > 18) and (x <= 24):
        return'Night'
    elif (x <= 6):
        return'Late Night'
    
# Create the time of day variable
data['time_of_day'] = data['time'].apply(f)
    In [11]:
    # Extract weekday from start time
import datetime
import calendar

def weekday_from_date(year,month, day):
    return calendar.day_name[
        datetime.date(year=year, month=month, day=day).weekday()
    ]
data['year'] = data['start_time'].dt.year
data['month'] = data['start_time'].dt.month
data['day'] = data['start_time'].dt.day

data['weekday'] = data.apply(lambda x: weekday_from_date(x['year'], x['month'], x['day']), axis=1)

def build_boxplots(data: pd.DataFrame, 
                  x_feature:str, 
                  y_feature:str,
                  ): 
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
    ax = sb.boxplot(data=data, x=x_feature, y=y_feature)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 60)
    plt.title(f"Distribution of minutes spent according to {feature}")
    plt.show()

    Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

    The interactions between duration of bike rides and age differed among different genders showing that while age has a effect on the bike ride duration, the gender of the rider in a similar age group also has an effect

    Conclusions¶

  • In the exploration, Preliminary findings show that the average bike ride lasted for about 13minutes with most rides lasting for between 1-60 minutes.

  • There were more male riders and the average age of the rider was between 20-40 years.

  • There were also more bike rides during the day than at night and more on weekdays than on weekends.

  • I found that there was a relationship between the time of day a ride of day was taken and the duration of time. Riders rode longer during the day than at night

  • However the day of the week did not have much effect on the average duration of bike rides. The duration of rides increased as age increased across all genders. However, males have the lowest ride time across the all a groups.
